@article{Riehl2012,
abstract = {The dynamics of Early to Middle Bronze Age agriculture are investigated by means of archaeobotany and stable carbon isotope analysis and factors leading to variation from the general trend are discussed. Although a general trend of environmental stress through increasing aridity is indicated in the stable carbon isotopes of archaeobotanical barley remains of Middle Bronze Age sites (from ca. 2000 BC), archaeobotanical patterns indicate that this effect was insufficient to lead to an area-wide abandonment of settlements.Continuous change of environmental parameters such as climate variation, anthropogenic impact on the environment, population growth, cultural and ethical diversity in human groups, and the impossibility of finding a consensus on questions important to decision-making can lead to very diverse effects in economy and question the validity of sustainability concepts. ?? 2011 Elsevier Ltd.},
annote = {Extracted Annotations (3/2/2015, 7:09:07 PM)"Supra-regional studies, however, suggest that we should neither expect singular causes nor congeneric or simultaneous effects and reactions when dealing with causation in human systems ( Riehl and Bryson, 2007; Riehl, 2009b; Wilkinson, 2004 )." (p. 1)"several hundred thousand plant remains have been collected from 11 archaeological sites (Tell Atchana, Kinet H{\"{o}}y{\"{u}}k, Tell Mozan, Tell Halaf, Tell Tawila, Emar, Tell el ' Abd, Qatna, Tell Fadous, Zeraqon and Zincirli) using the standard methods in archaeobotanical sampling of Near Eastern site" (p. 2)"Agronomic references on water requirements of the crops have been used to assess their potential sensitivity to increasing aridity ( Riehl, 2009a )." (p. 2)"It is well known that C3 plants growing under reduced water availability have reduced carbon fi xation from CO 2 in their vegetative tissues due to reduced photosynthesis by stomatal closure that protects plants from dehydration ( Araus et al.,1997; Ehleringer et al., 1986; Farquhar et al., 1982 ). Despite the dominant role of water availability in carbon fi xation, the causes of variation in D 13 C are complex and not always straightforward, as many other factors can be involved ( Dawson et al., 2002 ). In arid and semi-arid environments, however, increased water stress accounts for the largest part of D 13 C variation (3 e 6 {\&} according to Tieszen, 1991 ). In this type of environment, stress caused by salinity can in fl uence D 13 C variation in the same way, although this aspect seems to have been investigated mainly in halophytes. Low nutrient content in soils can result in D 13 C variation in the other direction (3 e 5 {\&} ), thus neutralizing the signal of water stress (see Tieszen, 1991 , table 1, p. 230). Tieszen (1991) suggests that this aspect is a minor concern in archeology." (p. 2)"In presence, proportion, and ubiquity, barley ( Hordeum spp.) is consistently the main cereal crop throughout the Early and Middle Bronze Age Near East. Today, a dominance of barley is a common feature in arid and semi-arid environments due to its short reproduction cycle preventing the crop from extensive drought stress" (p. 3)"The proportions of the hulled wheats emmer ( Triticum dicoccum ) and einkorn ( Triticum monococcum ) were particularly low in central North Syria during the Early Bronze Age. In contrast, the ubiquity of emmer is high in this area, indicating a regular use of this species, while einkorn, the cereal with the lowest yield structure and relatively high water requirements, seems to be near extinct in the whole Near East by the Middle Bronze Age. Emmer is considered a highly drought-resistant species due to its high waterholding capacity, and it can also be considered with high probability a salt-tolerant species, and therefore an ef fi cient cereal crop in arid environments (for details see Riehl, 2009a )." (p. 3)"Gr ape ( Vitis vinifera L. ssp. vinifera ) was cultivated over a large area during the Early Bronze Age, although in larger proportions mainly in areas with modern mean annual precipitation above 400 mm. Cultivation during the Early Bronze Age seems to have been practiced considerably southward of the natural distribution of the wild progenitor ( V. vinifera ssp. sylvestris ). Allowing for fewer analyzed Middle Bronze Age sites, grape cultivation generally seems to be reduced during this period, particularly in the central part of northern Syria." (p. 3)"In all, the archaeobotanical crop patterns indicate disappearance or reduction in drought-susceptible species, and in particular in fl ax, garden pea, and grape in many areas of the Near East from the Early to the Middle Bronze Age, while drought-tolerant species tend to increase or remain unchanged" (p. 3)"The correlation with the 4.200 BP event can be further speci fi ed for some cases, such as Tell Mozan on the upper Khabur. The archaeobotanical evidence from the site supports major fl uctuations toward the end of the Early Bronze Age. It indicates a short-term shift to increased moisture during the fi nal phase of the Early Bronze Age (c. 2100 e 2000 BC), directly related to a shift in crop production from barley to free-threshing wheat for roughly one century, and another shift back to barley, accompanied by dryland wild species after 2000 BC ( Riehl, 2010 )." (p. 3)", a particular characteristic of the Early Bronze Age Euphrates region is extremely high proportions of" (p. 3)"The cultivation of olive ( Olea europaea L.) was relatively restricted to an area close to the Mediterranean coast during the Early Bronze Age and became regionally even more reduced in the Middle Bronze Age." (p. 3)"barley in some sites, a pattern that has been interpreted as a kind of " monoculture " of barley in Early Bronze Age Euphrates settlements in contrast to the upper Khabur settlements ( Riehl and Bryson, 2007 ). During the Middle Bronze Age, however, there seems to be a slightly contrary trend to somewhat higher barley proportions in the Khabur area and lower proportions in the Euphrates region." (p. 4)"The archaeobotanical remains of three sites (Tell Mozan, Tell Brak, Tell Atij) roughly dating between 2600 and 2300 BC) on a north-south line of roughly 100 km, spanning a precipitation regime from 100 to 150 mm at Tell Atij to 200 e 250 mm at Tell Mozan in the months from December to February, support the conclusion on the importance of the precipitation regime for the composition of the archaeobotanical assemblage. Attribute plots of speci fi c taxa further con fi rm this, with high proportions in plant taxa of open and disturbed habitats ( Astragalus spp., Liliaceae) at Tell Atij, high proportions of barley at Tell Brak and of freethreshing wheat at Tell Mozan ( Riehl and Bryson, 2007 )." (p. 5)"Another difference in rainfall patterns in the western and eastern Fertile Crescent is the number and timing of main precipitation periods with the typical Mediterranean winter precipitation regime in the west and a regime with two rainy seasons in the east, in the beginning of spring and the end of autumn and with a winter drought that is less pronounced and shorter than the summer drought ( Alex, 1985 ). These different regimes correlate well with the natural distribution of wild olive and win" (p. 5)"While at Soreq Cave ( Bar-Matthews and Ayalon, 1998; 2011 ) drier conditions are indicated in der d 18 O record at 4200 BP and ancient water levels at Lake Kineret ( Hazan et al., 2005 ) started to decrease at the same time, carbonate cutans in southeast Turkey stopped growing roughly around 4100 BP ( Pustovoytov et al., 2007 ). A closer look at the oxygen isotopic record from Lake Van ( Lemcke and Sturm, 1997; Wick et al., 2003 ) shows long-term trends of increasing aridity after 4000 BP rather than speci fi c peaks, which would correlate with an individual event." (p. 5)"A major methodological problem is differences in chronological resolution in all of the mentioned records, as the number of measurements within a certain sequence determines the number and chronological placement of fl uctuations creating locally individual patterns (compare the measured d 18 O record and the smoothed curved in Bar-Matthews and Ayalon, 2011 )." (p. 5)"Most of the archaeological sites in Syria lie in an area of 200 e 400 mm of modern mean annual precipitation, i.e., in an area very sensitive to any decrease in precipitation. There are two possible scenarios for the past. Under an assumption that modern and ancient mean precipitation are more or less equal, the settlements in regions below the critical 400 mm isohyet should have been under permanent risk of crop failure in occasionally occurring drought years. Alternatively the ancient isohyets may have been further south, allowing these settlements to develop a prosperous agriculture." (p. 5)"The mean actual precipitation in a series of drought years, such as between 1957 and 1961, may be 100 e 200 mm below the longterm mean annual precipitation (i.e., the 250 mm isohyet in such drought years is equivalent to the 400 mm isohyet of the long-term mean), causing a continuous sequence of crop failures in areas with long-term mean annual precipitation below 400 mm ( Wirth,1971 ). Recent research on variation in precipitation shows reasonable evidence of multi-year to decadal cyclicity in the past ( Touchan et al., 1999, 2003 ), i.e., the occurrence of droughts for duration of three years or longer" (p. 6)"A strongly specialized population may perceive a drought more intense than a group of people with highly diversi fi ed subsistence strategies, which may result in quite different behavior between these groups, but also within the groups, as the studies by Kates (1970) and by Heathcote (1980 ; there e.g. table 4.9) impressively show" (p. 6)----------Riehl{\_}Variability in ancient Near Eastern environmental and agricultural development.pdf
