@article{Freeman2014,
abstract = {We compare the robustness of food supplies to annual variation in rainfall within two different agricultural systems: a generalist system with one type of agent who cultivates both maize and agave, and a specialist system composed of two types of agents who cultivate either maize or agave and are able to exchange. When mean rainfall is relatively high and less variable or relatively low and more variable, food supplies in the specialist system are more robust than in the generalist system. However, at intermediate levels of mean rainfall and variability, food supplies in the specialist system are less robust than those in the generalist system. Our analysis suggests that conflicts of interest and their associated costs constrain the development of specialization in some environments. When considering the robustness of social-ecological systems, it is important to consider “for whom a coupled social and ecological system is robust?”},
annote = {Extracted Annotations (5/3/2015, 5:58:08 PM)
"Finally, by treating U T as a parameter, we assume that the total area that farmers devote to a particular crop (a decision based on many years of accumulated experience) changes more slowly than the choices that a farmer makes about the amount of maize or agave to gift on an annual basis (a decision based on annual rainfall variation)." (p. 299)
"The rainfall-productivity function does not consider how too much water would impact the productivity of maize" (p. 300)
"As a perennial plant, an agave population will exhibit age structure with individuals distributed across different cohorts." (p. 300)
they use density dependent growth for agave. should we do the same for sheep? (note on p.300)
 
"The exchange dynamics in our model system occur in a social market (Fiske 1992 ) as opposed to a monetized market (Heyman and Ariely 2004 ). The logic of exchange in social markets is often based on ritual and kin-based obligations rather than maximizing profit per se (Henrich et al . 2004 ; Sahlins 1972 ; Mauss 2006 )" (p. 300)
"A famine event of length i is simply the number of consecutive years when the minimum level of food required by a given representative agent is not achieved." (p. 302)
"When robustness is assessed in terms of discrete famine events, the food supply of the agave specialists is less vulnerable than the food supply of the generalist and maize specialists for all levels of mean rainfall. Maize specialists, on the other hand, experience more famine events than the generalist, except when mean rainfall drops to 55 units. At first glance, these results suggest that specialization provides a big advantage for agave specialists, but giving up their direct access to maize results in a subtle vulnerability." (p. 303)
"The agave specialists reduce their total famine events by eating excess agave in good years and storing their gifted maize. This strategy buffers the agave specialists against occasional dry years that wipe out juvenile cohorts of agave; however, the potential exists for dry years to occur consecutively causing successive cohorts of agave to fail. Under these conditions, agave yields may drop to zero for a decade at a time and agave specialists experience, on average, a large number of total famine years. This means that over an average 100-year time interval, the agave specialists spend almost a third of the time (31.1 years) in famine, even when mean rainfall is 100 units! By specializing, the agave specialists trade-off robustness to frequent, small deficits in rainfall for extreme vulnerability to less frequent, large deficits in rainfall." (p. 303)
"can food preferences be easily redefined, or are they entrenched by high social or physiological costs?" (p. 303)
"The solution that maximizes robustness for the group as a whole does not necessarily confer equal advantages to all group members." (p. 305)
"Our comparison of models indicates that in some social-ec ological conditions a specialized system with exchange outperform s a generalist system, in terms of the robustness of farmers ' supply of food to variation in rainfall." (p. 306)
"These observations suggest that to increase their robustness to famine, farmers in productive and less variable environments or extremely variable and unproductive environments should adopt a specialist strategy rather than be generalists." (p. 306)
"Our results are consistent with the long known pattern in ecology that specialization is more common in productive and less variable environments (Pianka 1973 )." (p. 306)
"We hypothesize that social diversity based on specialization and exchange may be constrained in environments where the production of resources is highly uncertain or unproductive due to the emergence of conflicts of interest between social actors." (p. 306)
"Cashdan ( 2001 ) has suggested that in subsistence-oriented human economies, the formation of specialization and exchange systems may occur in association with ethnic distinctions. For example, she has observed a negative correlation between ethnic diversity and inter-annual variation in rainfall, which could be explained by the emergence of conflicts of interest between members of different ethnic groups, or, as in our analysis, potential specialists, in uncertain environments." (p. 306)
"Thus, one hypothesis is that an agricultural economy based on specialization in maize and agave is more limited by inter-annual deviations in precipitation than the mean amount of precipitation. If a specialist system developed along the northern frontier and then climate shifted, even slightly increasing inter-annual variability in rainfall, this change would have strained the social relationships necessary for a specialist syste m to operate and possibly lead to a trajectory of social dissolution. Alternatively, it could trigger social tactics to coerce specialists to continue planting crops in ratios that were not in the interests of some farmers." (p. 307)
"Irrigation, however, provides an advantage in semi-arid environments by boosting the reliability of harvest (Mabry 2005 ). Thus, the addition of irrigation could significantly improve the robustness of the maize specialists ' food supply to drought. It is interesting, therefore, to note that irrigation ditches are evidenced in the Malpaso Valley floodplain near the site of La Quemada (Elliott et al . 2010 ). The irrigation of maize and specialization in agave production may go hand-in-hand because a sufficient degree of reliability in maize production is necessary for a specialist system to function" (p. 307)
